e whether to accept a temporary memory-graft to learn ledger-craft faster, knowing something personal will be erased.\",\n        \"Obtain a certified transcript for presentation to the Vigil and Triune.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Lerrin Vale\", \"lines\": \"We ask the bones to remember for us, and they do, humming the past in tones even the wind respects. We ask them to forget, and they rarely oblige, because forgetting is a kind of betrayal the ribs do not allow. This ledger does not wish to be known, its ink bound to sleep except beneath true moonshard light, but light is a patient interrogator and here it yields. See how the tide of silver curls toward names we have heard in grief and rumor: Danka Suth, a scribe who sold his hands, and this tight mark for R. Mestri bound to the instruction ‘Delay the breath one bell.’ A city could drown in that bell, and the ledger knows it, and the bones know it, and so must we if we are to keep faith with the Hollow Oath.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Aerin Rell\", \"lines\": \"The bones taught me that wind is a blade that spares no oathbreaker, and I have no wish to flinch from its edge. If a graft will give me the cipher’s tongue for a spell, I will pay the price, because there are children whose names the Echo should never have to learn. I have lost a song before in these halls when I begged a memory from marrow, and though it left an ache where a lullaby used to live, that ache was lighter than a deck-load of mourners. I would lose another small piece of myself rather than watch the Chainhouse lift a coffin because we were too proud to pay in memory. But I will not trade so much that I forget why I stand on these ribs, or who I swore to guard when I first lifted the rite-striker under a clean sky I was forbidden to sound.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Jarik Rell\", \"lines\": \"You keep cutting strips from your own heart like it is spare rigging, sister, and I keep wondering when you will reach the part that cannot be knotted back. Yet look at these pages and hear me: the scoring in the diary matches the moth-wings carved beneath the catwalk, and those marks align with Danka’s shifts just as tight as a well-spliced line. This is an inside haul, tidy and rehearsed, and every bell we give them is a bell they use to grease another bolt or cut another sling. I will carry a certified transcript to Spinegate and swear before the Seat that this is no street-thief’s mischief but a braided scheme. But I need you to decide what you are willing to give tonight, because the Vigil can hold a storm, not a civil war between guilds if the truth arrives late and toothless.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Lerrin Vale\", \"lines\": \"The Echo Hall is open for your names, and when you speak them they will come back to us long after our bones have chosen quiet, which is humbling and useful both. I can prepare a memory-graft that teaches you the ledger’s secret hand for a night and a morning, and I can lock it to fade before the next Lanterning, but every graft exacts its price, and marrow is a ledger more honest than this eel-skin ever was. The sealed codex waits as well, the one that tells how the heart was ferried south to the Drum of Reeds and why a seat must be filled when the city quarrels with itself, but codices will not stand up in court unless a living voice swears to them. Take this moonshard lens and this scribe’s grid, and we will let the Moon teach us how the coin ran where the wind could not. When it is done, I will stamp a transcript with the Archive’s cold seal and the Vigil will have words that do not blur under heat or fear.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Aerin Rell\", \"lines\": \"Let the Echo carry our names and hold them like lanterns in the dark long after we are ash and memory, and let me carry the weight until the Hall must lift it with me. I will walk this transcript across the ribs, past those who say they own the wind and those who pretend to own the r