kes itself known in a quieter way when you try to hum during the stamping, and the tune you reach for will not come, leaving only the shape of absence and the bare certainty that it used to calm you before gale drills. The Vigil and the Archive both gain confidence in your testimony, and the Triune’s clerks cannot easily dismiss a grafted expert who admits the price of her knowledge in open record. In later inquiries, the pattern you learned lingers like a faint watermark, granting you swifter insight into ciphers and bribe paths even after the graft fades, while a rumor grows that the paladin who hears bones also taught them to speak in ink.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C2\", \"title\": \"Refuse the memory-graft and trust your own ear, your brother’s grit, and the Archive’s method.\", \"text\": \"You place your palm over the moonshard’s glow and slide it gently away, as if shading a lantern from a child’s eyes during a storm. Your vow is not to win with every tool, you remind yourself, but to win without breaking what you mean to save, and sometimes that means choosing patience over power. Jarik exhales, not in relief but in readiness, and leans in with the rafter’s diary as if the two of you were back in the Undershadows counting lamp routes by fingertip. Lerrin nods once, approval and worry married together, and unrolls clean grids and oils the ledger’s page corners so nothing smears under your hands. The Echo Hall listens while you work by the honest pace of breath and quill, turning fragments into a braided rope that can hold a city’s weight if thrown true.\", \"outcome\": \"Decoding takes longer and your eyes burn with it, but the work yields patterns all the same: Roa Mestri’s role as a payer and messenger, Danka Suth’s shifts aligning with scored signals, and a horn log window that fits the ‘delay’ order like a hidden notch. The transcript is sealed closer to the contested bell than you would like, forcing Jarik to sprint for Spinegate while you carry the codex after him with Breathkeeper speed and a prayer you are not sure you believe in tonight. The Triune’s clerks raise brows at the absence of a graft but respect the clear corroboration, and Captain-Magistrate Sorn Ilt gives you a curt nod that says patience is a kind of courage he can still recognize under pressure. You keep every fragment of yourself, and when the day demands a song to steady frightened children you find it waiting in your throat like a friend who has kept the bench warm. The cost appears in a different ledger: some doors that would have swung on the mystique of grafted expertise now open only with effort, and you will have to argue harder in later sessions to be heard over the thunder of factions.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C3\", \"title\": \"Break from the Archive to confront Danka Suth before the transcript is carried, risking a warning ripple through the plot.\", \"text\": \"You catch the ledger’s most damning lines in your fist like a rope you refuse to drop, and you tell Jarik to hold the seal while you find the hand that tied these knots. The walk from the Archive to the Undershadows is a descent through lamps and whispers, and every deck you pass reminds you of how long a bell can be when spent in fear. Danka’s nook stinks of seal-pitch and old ink, and his eyes flicker like minnows when your shadow crosses the threshold. You speak the words ‘delay the breath’ and watch his lips bleach, and you lay your Oathplate Shield across the doorway so his courage will have to climb over it to run. Your voice stays calm but it fills the tiny room with gale and river both, and you promise him a fair hearing if he trades you truth for the chance to keep his name off the Echo’s lips tonight.\", \"outcome\": \"Danka cracks like kiln glaze at a sour firing, blurting Roa Mestri’s name and panting that he thought buying a bell would only keep guild pride intact, not drown anyone, and he thrusts a token toward you that matches a Riverfoot runner’s pass. The confrontation shakes the street and draws ears, which means the warning runs upriver faster than you do, and by the time Jarik carries the transcript to Spinegate the River Lords have already moved to tidy their house. Some ledger scraps vanish from expected places and one scribe goes suddenly ‘on leave,’ but you gain a living confession on oathstone that can be carried like a burning brand into any chamber that pretends not to see. The Vigil looks at you with a mix of gratitude and irritation for moving without their badge, and Sorn Ilt grinds his teeth while he signs a protective custody writ that probably saves Danka’s life before dawn. The plot adapts, but so do you, and what you bring to the Triune is not just ink and inference but breath and fear and the cracked voice of a man who never meant to be a knife in the city’s ribs.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C4\", \"title\": \"Invite the Moth Lanterns into the decoding quietly, seeking their signal-craft to distinguish mimic marks from true wings.\", \"text\": \"You send a bone-chip message down the Archive’s delivery chute, and the answer is a lantern-flicker against the distant lattice that only Scale-born ears would swear had a sound. Thia Mol steps from a column of stacked scroll crates as if she has always belonged to the hush of libraries, her smile both apology and dare in equal measure. You show her the moth-etched marks and the diary’s rubbings, and you ask not for innocence but for knowledge, because you know pride kills as surely as knives when proof is thin. She tests you with a question about why you did not come sooner, and you tell her the truth, which is that you carry oaths like full pails and sometimes you spill when you hurry. She agrees to read the wings for you, on condition that her lantern-signal never be used to burn the poor, and the Echo Hall takes that promise into itself like a second light.\", \"outcome\": \"The Lantern-Queen’s eyes pick the forgeries apart as neatly as a rigger unpicking a bad spl